{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":25701,"record_hash":"sha256:5a4dcc45b18a41a20127f5258ad3612a360928a4f3d9af93fd59997553feb6e1","timestamp":"2026-05-11T10:11:23.962Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes. The cleanest fix is in **GitMeta**, not `but-agentlog`.\n\n`but-agentlog` is already storing transcript records in the right primary shape: one transcript record per `list_values` row, with large records moved to Git blobs. The bad shape is GitMeta’s `metadata_log.value`, which currently stores a giant JSON batch for the append operation. That creates a single huge log row even though the real data already lives in `list_values`.\n\nThe obvious GitMeta fix:\n\n- Treat `metadata_log` as a dirty-key/audit journal, not a second copy of collection data.\n- For collection operations like `push` / `set_add`, log a small value such as `\"\"`, `\"[]\"`, or maybe `{\"count\": N}`.\n- Let reads/serialization use the actual normalized storage:\n  - list content from `list_values`\n  - set content from `set_values`\n  - current metadata shape from `metadata`\n\nThis seems safe because `get_modified_since()` uses `metadata_log` for target/key/operation, but joins current `metadata` and serialization reads current data through `get_all_metadata()`. The big `metadata_log.value` is not the authoritative transcript source.\n\nA `but-agentlog` workaround would be chunking the import into smaller batches, but that only turns one giant log row into many medium log rows. It does not remove the duplicate storage, and it adds more capture complexity. So I would avoid that.\n\nMy recommendation: make a small GitMeta change so list/set append-style log rows are compact. That should cut the SQLite DB notably without changing the agentlog data model.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T10:11:23.962Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}